T1  - A Study of the Effects of Quantitative Training
AU  - Eliason, Alan L.
Y1  - 1972/06/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254906
DO  - 10.5465/254906
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 147
EP  - 158
VL  - 15
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this study, two groups of subjects, one with advanced quantitative training, the other with little or no quantitative training, were exposed to an interactive-decision simulation gaming model to test, experimentally, possible effects of quantitative training. The findings show that the quantitative group achieved a higher level of game-performance but were unable to justify why gaming decisions were necessary. Other conclusions identify possible areas of weakness in quantitative training methodology.
AB  - In this study, two groups of subjects, one with advanced quantitative training, the other with little or no quantitative training, were exposed to an interactive-decision simulation gaming model to test, experimentally, possible effects of quantitative training. The findings show that the quantitative group achieved a higher level of game-performance but were unable to justify why gaming decisions were necessary. Other conclusions identify possible areas of weakness in quantitative training methodology.
