TY  - JOUR
T1  - LPC as a Modifier of Leader-Follower Relationships
AU  - Jones, Halsey R.
AU  - Johnson, Michael
Y1  - 1972/06/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/254910
DO  - 10.5465/254910
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 185
EP  - 196
VL  - 15
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study on how least preferred co-worker (LPC) questionnaire scores of leaders and followers can affect industrial relations. LPC scores are used to measure leadership styles such as autocratic, democratic, and laissez-faire. However, past research did not clearly define the impact of LPC scores on superior-subordinate relations in particular situations. This study focuses on job satisfaction and organizational climate based on high and low scoring superiors and subordinates, and performance ratings based on LPC scores. The author makes conclusions based on the study results.
AB  - The article presents a study on how least preferred co-worker (LPC) questionnaire scores of leaders and followers can affect industrial relations. LPC scores are used to measure leadership styles such as autocratic, democratic, and laissez-faire. However, past research did not clearly define the impact of LPC scores on superior-subordinate relations in particular situations. This study focuses on job satisfaction and organizational climate based on high and low scoring superiors and subordinates, and performance ratings based on LPC scores. The author makes conclusions based on the study results.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/254910
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/254910
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

